class CountIntervals {
    Map<Integer, Integer> intervals = new HashMap<>();

    public CountIntervals() {
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        intervals.put(left, intervals.getOrDefault(left, 0) + 1);
        intervals.put(right, intervals.getOrDefault(right, 0) + 1);
    }

    public int count() {
        int count = 0;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : intervals.entrySet()) {
            count += entry.getValue();
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use a HashMap to store the count of integers in each interval. When adding an interval, we update the count for the left and right endpoints. When counting, we iterate over the HashMap and add the count of each interval to the final result. The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate over the HashMap once, and the space complexity is O(n) because we store n intervals in the HashMap.

